config.text: Guia de Ajuda

Search is configured to find features, records, or locations in the map based on specific layers and locators. Typing search terms into the box will automatically begin to return results. The layers and locators available for an application may vary based on the application's audience and or purpose. If there are multiple search sources, you can choose which ones to search.

Selection Tools located at the top of the map pane, this set of tools allows you to interactively select one or many features from the map. The down arrow will open a selection dialog that displays different selection options (below). This tool will select features from all layers that are visible or turned on in the map. The X shaped icon will clear all selections. Features selected with this tool will also be selected in the attribute table and will be available for use in the "Near Me" tool. A count of selected features will be displayed at the bottom of the map and at the bottom of the attribute table if the selected layer is included in the attribute table.

1. Address Locator Searches: This application uses a view of ESRI's World Locator service that is limited to the extent of Leon County.
  2. Street Address: Enter a Street Address or Street Name the locator will begin to offer candidates as you type.
  3. Street Intersection: Enter the name of two streets that intersect with an ampersand between them. example: "Monroe St & College Ave" the locator will offer intersection candidates and zoom to the one you select.
  4. Longitude/Latitude: This locator can find coordinate locations in Latitude and Longitude (decimal degrees). Coordinates values should be entered separated by a comma with Longitude first followed by Latitude (X,Y). For example -84.279945, 30.439375
  5. Places: The ESRI Locator can also search for place names like "Wal-Mart", "Hospital", or a park name.
  6. Layer Searches:
  7. Parcels: To search the Parcel layer, enter a Parcel TaxID, Parcel Address, or Owner Name.
  8. Subdivisions: To search the Subdivision layer, enter a Subdivision Name or Header ID Number.
  9. Common Places: To search the Common Places layer, Enter a Place Name or Address

The Table or Attribute Table widget displays multiple interactive attribute tables that are associated with layers in the map. The table widget includes options to select, search, and filter, layers and download tabular results. It can be accessed from the tab at the bottom of the application.

Elevation Profile generates and displays an elevation profile based on an input path created by drawing or selecting single or multi-segment lines on the map. The widget can display elevation profile lines for the ground and for selected line features. It can also display the elevation of intersecting features along a profile or within a buffered distance of the profile on the map. You can view slope and elevation statistics and export the data for each profile and the intersecting layers.

Near Me or Buffer Analysis Use this tool to generate lists of parcels, addresses, and HOA contacts by proximity to a set location on the map. The tool uses selected features on the map to set the source for the adjustable buffer. Lists generated by this tool can be downloaded in CSV format which is compatible with most spreadsheet software and can be used in mail merge and label functions.


You can set the buffer source by:

  1. Using the drawing tools in the widget to draw shapes on the map,
  2. Using the search tool at the top of the map,
  3. Using the select tool at the upper left corner of the map.

config.text: Share - The Share tool allows you to share this app by posting a link to a social media account, sending an email with a link, or embedding it in a website or blog. It also provides a URL and QR code of the app. It shares the entire app. You can share links that include URL parameters, meaning the links can open the app to certain pages, have certain features selected, and more.
Layers

tooltip.name: Layers

config.text:
This panel displays a predefined list of layers that you can turn on/off by clicking on the check box next to the layer's name in the list. 


Hints:

  1. You can search for layers in the list by name using the search tool at the top of the list.
  2. Some layers are grouped, to expand the group click on the arrow in front of the check box.
  3. If you can't see a layer that is turned on, try zooming in. Some layers are set to be visible only at certain zoom levels. Layer options like transparency, filtering, attributes, and download can be accessed by clicking on the three dots - - to the right of the layer name.
  4. Layers can be moved up and down in the stack by clicking the six dots to the left of the layer name and dragging the layer up or down.
  5. To see a legend for a specific layer, click the small legend icon to the right of its name.
Legend

tooltip.name: Legend

config.text: This panel displays the symbols for map layers that are currently visible or clicked on in the map's "Layers" tool. Basemap layers are not included in the legend.
Basemap

tooltip.name: Legend

config.text: This panel displays the basemap gallery. You can change the background map by clicking on individual thumbnail images. The gallery includes both ESRI and locally maintained TLCGIS basemaps along with multiple years of aerial photography for you to choose from. More Information
Add Data

tooltip.name: Legend

config.text:
This panel provides access to additional layers that may not be included in the map. Use the search options below to add layers. Layers will only remain in the map during your current web session, if you close the map page they will be removed.


Search Options

  1. TLCGIS Layer Gallery - TLCGIS' vast gallery of curated authoritative layers that are publicly available. Use this tool to search the layer gallery and add the layers you find to the map. TLCGIS Layer Gallery
  2. My Content - If you have an ArcGIS Online account and you are logged in, you can add layers from your user content.
  3. My Organization - If you have an ArcGIS Online account and you are logged in, you can add layers that are shared within your organization.
  4. Living Atlas - The ArcGIS Living Atlas of the World is the foremost collection of geographic information from around the globe. It includes maps, apps, and data layers to support your work. More...


Other Options

  1. URL - If you have access to a map service layer URL from ArcGIS Server, WMS, WMT, WFS, KML, CSV, or GeoJSON you can add the link here.
  2. File - If you have a local file in any of the following formats, you can upload it here.
  3. Shapefile (zipped),
  4. CSV,
  5. KML,
  6. GeoJSON,
  7. GPX
Feature Info

tooltip.name: Legend

config.text:
This panel displays popup information for selected features within specified layers. You can select which layer's popup you would like to display from the pick list at the top right.


Tips

  1. You can minimize the on-screen popup and use this panel to save screen space.
  2. Layers must be visible/turned on in the map to be selectable.
Filter

tooltip.name: Legend

config.text: This tool applies predefined filters to specified layers in the map. Make sure the layer you are filtering is turned on/visible in the map. Filtered layers will be visibly filtered on the map and in the attribute table.
Bookmarks

tooltip.name: Legend

config.text: This panel displays a list of spatial bookmarks. Clicking on a bookmark in the list will change the extent of the map by zooming to a predefined location. The list of bookmarks may include most well known communities and places in Tallahassee and Leon County or locations specific to the purpose of this application.
Print

tooltip.name: Legend

config.text:
This panel displays the print tool. The Print tool allows you to print web maps and includes options for previewing extents, selecting layouts, and more. The print tool will generate a downloadable web graphic of the current map in PDF, GIF, EPS, PNG, SVG, or JPG format. The default file type is PDF.


Printing Tips:

  1. To see advanced options, click the arrow next to "Advanced".
  2. Links to printed documents will appear in the Results tab (top).
  3. Printed documents are temporary and will typically be deleted after 1 hour.
  4. Be sure to download your results if you intend to keep them.
  5. Print Quality can be adjusted by increasing the DPI (Dots Per Inch). Note: Increasing the DPI too high may cause the print job to time-out and fail.


Layout Template Options:

  1. Letter Landscape (8.5 X 11)
  2. Letter Portrait (8.5 X 11)
  3. Tabloid Landscape (11X17)
  4. Tabloid Portrait (11X17)
  5. Map Only (Adjustable Dimensions in pixels)
Measure

tooltip.name: Legend

config.text:
This panel displays the Measurement tool. The Measurement tool calculates distances, perimeters, and areas in the map.


Note: Measurements made with this tool are reasonably accurate. However, they are not a survey and should not be misconstrued as survey accurate measurements.


Distance: To measure a linear distance, click the icon that looks like a ruler with a line on top. Click the map where you want to start the measurement and click once for every vertex on the line you want to measure. Double-click to complete the line.


Area: To measure an area and its perimeter, click the icon that looks like a ruler with a square around it. Click the map where you want to start the measurement, and click once for every vertex of the area you want to measure. Double-click to complete the area.

Tips:

  1. The default unit of measurement is set to Imperial (inches, feet, square feet, miles) but you can change the unit setting as needed.
  2. Both the Distance and Area tools will will snap to features in the map like parcel boundaries. They will not snap to features in the basemap.
  3. Measurement labels and graphics will appear on printed maps.
Draw

tooltip.name: Legend

config.text:
This panel displays the Draw tool. The draw tool will allow you to create simple graphics for text, points, lines, and polygons on the map. You can add measurements to drawn graphics for coordinate position, length, perimeter, and area.


Note: This tool remains active when the panel is closed. To deactivate the tool, deactivate any draw tools that are active by clicking on them.
Coordinates

tooltip.name: Legend

config.text:
This panel displays the Coordinates tool. The Coordinates tool displays X/Y coordinate values for locations on the webmap. You can get coordinates based on the pointer's location or by adding points.


Default Output Coordinate System:

Latitude/Longitude (WGS 1984 decimal degrees)


Optional Output Coordinate System:

State Plane (NAD1983 HARN Florida North FIPS 0903 Feet)


Note: The add point portion of this tool remains active when the panel is closed. You can deactivate the add point tool by clicking on it.
Edit

tooltip.name: Legend

config.text:
This panel displays the Editing tool. Active features in the map that are editable can be edited using this tool. You must have edit permissions for any editable layer. With this tool, you can select an existing feature and edit it's geometry or update its attributes. You can also create new features by clicking a symbol icon under create features and clicking a location on the map.


Note: The create features portion of this tool remains active when the panel is closed. You can deactivate the add point tool by clicking on it.
